# Code Quality

## General

- Minimize scope: smallest correct diff; no drive-by refactors
- Match existing naming, ESM imports, and file layout
- One module = one responsibility (map, players, network, render, etc.)
- Prefer pure functions for game logic (pathfinding, collision, damage)

## Testing

- Run `npm test` before committing; all tests must pass
- Add unit tests for new pure functions and bug fixes (see [unit-tests.mdc](unit-tests.mdc))
- Use `tests/helpers/fixtures.js` for deterministic map data
- Socket/UI-only changes: document manual smoke test if no unit test applies

## Documentation

- **Public modules** (exported functions/classes): JSDoc on non-obvious APIs
- **Complex logic** (pathfinding, combat formulas): brief comment on *why*, not *what*
- Do not add comments that restate the code
- Update README, CHANGELOG, and TODO when user-facing behavior changes

## Error handling

- Validate socket payloads on the server; emit `error` event with clear message
- Fail early on invalid input; never silently ignore bad client data
- Log server errors with context; avoid logging secrets

## Examples

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — vague, no validation
socket.on('move', (data) => { player.x += data.x; });

// ✅ GOOD — validated, server-authoritative
socket.on(EVENTS.MOVE, ({ direction }) => {
  if (!DIRECTION_DELTA[direction]) return;
  // collision check, then update
});
```
